Detecting Fraud Transactions by numerous Machine Learning technics¶

About this notebook:¶

The whole point of this notebook is to try catch up autoencoder representation of fraud transaction and compared the result of models which was learned on this prepared data by this algorithm with models fed by original data. We expect dimensionality reduction with the same or with the better results. The notebook consist:

  • Data analysis
  • Undersampling
  • PCA and TSNE
  • Autoencoder as data preporation for standard supervised algorithm: Logistic Regression, Random Forrest, SVM and XGBoost

Since this is a complex dataset, the following analyzes will be performed in the future::

  • Outlier detection
  • Oversampling

We will measure the performance mainly by AUROC and AUPRC

Data Information:¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud

The dataset contains transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders. This dataset presents transactions that occurred in two days, where we have 492 frauds out of 284,807 transactions. The dataset is highly unbalanced, the positive class (frauds) account for 0.172% of all transactions.

It contains only numerical input variables which are the result of a PCA transformation. Unfortunately, due to confidentiality issues, we cannot provide the original features and more background information about the data. Features V1, V2, … V28 are the principal components obtained with PCA, the only features which have not been transformed with PCA are 'Time' and 'Amount'. Feature 'Time' contains the seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset. The feature 'Amount' is the transaction Amount, this feature can be used for example-dependant cost-sensitive learning. Feature 'Class' is the response variable and it takes value 1 in case of fraud and 0 otherwise.

Perform PCA and TSNE on standarized Data Frame¶

Since we sampled from a normal distribution (0,1), the Central Limit Theorem implies that we will most likely have a mean similar to the original distribution - this will have the highest probability. But it still won't be perfect enough for us.

In [ ]:
df_mean = pd.concat([round(df.drop(columns = 'Class').mean(),5),round(df_X.mean(),5)], axis = 1).rename(columns = {0:'original', 1:'sample'})

As we can see, there is a significant difference in the mean between the sample DF and the original one - another example of what exactly the Central Limit Theorem state for. More specifically, this ensures that the average of the sample means will be similar to the original mean - once we select a large enough sample - but it does not ensure that the distribution will be identical to that of the original population.

That's why we will perform PCA and TSNE on transformed data:

As we can see, there is a significant difference between the two methods used in this dataset. Although in both cases we can see the differences between fraud transactions and non-fraud transactions - the TSNE algorithm performs better for our dataset. Our standardization on sampled Data Frame, especially for TSNE, helped visualize 2 groups of non-fraud transactions and also increased the density of fraud transactions. The bad news is that there are certainly some outliers among non-fraudulent transactions, but the good news is that we can confidently predict which transaction may be considered as a fraud.

Autoencoder¶

The autoencoder learns to represent the input data - it begins to pass through smaller and smaller layers and when it reaches a bottleneck it must recreate the original data. We will take adventage of it - we will try to learn how non-fraud transactions looks like and after that we will try to predict fraud transaction - we expect that it will be an anomaly-looking data for the model. The output for the fraud transactions should look easy to diffrenceite for the classification model. So we will combine encoder part and then pass it to 3 different model (Logistic Classifier, Random Forest and XGBoost).

We will use two architecture of Autoencoders:

  • Vanilla Autoencoder
  • Sparse Autoencoder
In [ ]:
df_standards_sample = df_standards.sample(n = df_frauds.shape[0]*4, random_state=22)
df_standards_sample = df_standards_sample.drop(columns='Class')

Vanilla Autoencoder¶

Following for me the most the most understandable definition:\ The most basic type of autoencoder, which consists of a decoder network that reconstructs the input from the compressed representation after the input has been compressed by an encoder network.

In [ ]:
# input layer 
input_layer = Input(shape=(df_standards_sample.shape[1],))

# encoder network
encoded = Dense(30, activation='elu')(input_layer)
encoded = Dense(25, activation='relu')(encoded)
encoded = Dense(20, activation='tanh')(encoded)
encoded = Dense(15, activation='elu')(encoded)
encoded = Dense(10, activation='relu')(encoded)
encoded = Dense(5, activation='tanh')(encoded) # bottleneck


# decoder network
decoded = Dense(10, activation='tanh')(encoded)
decoded = Dense(15, activation='elu')(decoded)
decoded = Dense(20, activation='tanh')(decoded)
decoded = Dense(25, activation='relu')(decoded)
decoded = Dense(30, activation='tanh')(decoded)

# output layer
output_layer = Dense(df_standards_sample.shape[1], activation='relu')(decoded)

# Early Stop
EarlyStop = EarlyStopping(monitor='accuracy', patience=25)
In [ ]:
autoencoder = Model(input_layer, output_layer)
autoencoder.compile(optimizer="adam", metrics=['accuracy'], loss="mse")

Sparse Autoencoders¶

One more time following for me the most understandable definition:\ A Sparse Autoencoder is a type of autoencoder that employs sparsity to achieve an information bottleneck. Specifically the loss function is constructed so that activations are penalized within a layer.

In [ ]:
## input layer 
input_layer = Input(shape=(df_standards_sample.shape[1],))

## encoder network
encoded = Dense(64, activation='elu', activity_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.0001))(input_layer)
encoded = Dense(32, activation='tanh', activity_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.0001))(encoded)
encoded = Dense(16, activation='elu', activity_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.0001))(encoded)
encoded = Dense(8, activation='relu', activity_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.0001))(encoded)


## decoder network part
decoded = Dense(16, activation='tanh')(encoded)
decoded = Dense(32, activation='elu')(decoded)
decoded = Dense(64, activation='tanh')(decoded)

## output layer
output_layer = Dense(df_standards_sample.shape[1], activation='relu')(decoded)

EarlyStop = EarlyStopping(monitor='accuracy', patience=25)

Summary¶

As we saw, there are almost no diffrences in performence between Undersampled Machine Learning and data prepared by Sparse Autoencoder.\ What is more, there is signifant change in features which comes into model: 30 against 16. We could try to make features selection for original Data Frame. However the strongest part of Autoencoder is that, it will do it for us with respect of the all valuable information from each features will be saved by it for the best performance.\ Even though we doesn't aquiare better result for it, we obtain quicker algorith which could be beneficial for bigger Data Frame (milions of bank transactions per year) and to tune algorith, which is fed by data prepared by Autoencoder - as we obtain a lot of copmutational power. For instance, evaluation of Cross Validation is on average 2 times quicker for Autoencoder dataset.
